To protect the animal species, dubbed a "national gem," China has set up 33 nature reserves with a combined area of 1.6 million hectares.By the end of 2004, arrow bamboo, the favorite food of giants, had blossomed on 7,420 hectares at the Baishuijiang State Nature Reserve in southern Gansu Province, a major habitat of pandas in China, according to a recent survey conducted by the nature reserve administration.Only around 1,600 pandas are believed to live in the wild, with some 300 of the sub-species living in the Qinling mountains, while the other 1,300 giant pandas live elsewhere in China, Xinhua said in a separate report.They ascribed the appearance of giant pandas in Fengxian County, located on the western section of Qinling Mountain, a major habitat for giant pandas, to the local government's strenuous efforts to restore and protect natural forest resources in the region over recent years.The giant panda is one of the world's most rare and endangered species, with an estimated some 1,000 living in the mountainous regions of Sichuan in southwest China, and northwestern Shaanxi and Gansu provinces.The discovery of panda traces in Fengxian County, northwest China's Shaanxi Province, demonstrates that the habitat of the rare creatures is expanding in this inland province, an official with the Shaanxi Provincial Forestry Bureau said.The bank at southwest China's Giant Panda Protection and Research Centre in the Wolong Nature Reserve in Sichuan province will be completed this year, the China Daily said.China has applied to the United Nations to make giant pandas' natural habitat in southwestern Sichuan province a world heritage area to help protect the endangered species, state press reported Tuesday.Flowering arrow bamboo is threatening a colony of endangered giant pandas in China but experts have come up with a plan to save them, state media said Monday.Currently more than 1,500 giant pandas live wild in China, according to a survey by the State Forestry Administration.China's endangered panda is migrating into forest areas restored by the government, the re-discovery of its dung in northern Shaanxi province indicates, state press reported Wednesday.China has 163 giant pandas in captivity.Giant pandas, said to have been around during the time of dinosaurs, are cited as a "national gem" of China.Three giant pandas living in Beijing Zoo will be sent to Wolong of Sichuan Province, southwest China, Wednesday and three others in Sichuan will fly to Beijing Friday, under an exchange program aimed to maintain the biodiversity of the giant panda population.There are only about 1,590 of the endangered species living in the wild, all in China, though the numbers have risen steadily in the past decade after plunging to around 1,100 in the 1980s."Now China has about 1,700 giant pandas and 76 percent of them live in Sichuan," said Yang, adding that the provincial government has obtained a financial support of more than 24 million yuan (2.